---
/**
 * About — the keeper of the camp.
 */
import BaseLayout from '../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageTitle from '../components/sections/PageTitle.astro';
import ImagePlaceholder from '../components/content/ImagePlaceholder.astro';
import CTASection from '../components/sections/CTASection.astro';
import { routes } from '../lib/i18n';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About the Camp"
  description="The person behind Camp Flaneuse: Elai, a motorhome named Ember, a few cats, and the slow construction of a freer life on the road."
  lang="en"
  translationUrl={routes.about.pt}
>
  <PageTitle
    overline="The keeper"
    title="About the Camp"
    lede="Every camp has someone who keeps the fire going and the notebooks dry. Here, that someone is Elai."
  />

  <article class="section about-body">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Camp Flaneuse is kept by <strong>Elai</strong> — a person who writes, draws, watches
          birds, and lives on the road in a motorhome named <strong>Ember</strong>, in the company
          of cats who did not sign up for this but have adapted with dignity.
        </p>

        <p>
          The short version: Camp Flaneuse began with a refusal of the version of life that put
          work at the center of everything — the speed, the constant proving, the feeling that
          rest had to be earned and attention had to be useful. Instead of optimizing that life,
          it seemed better to build a different one. Smaller. Slower. More attentive. With wheels.
        </p>

        <h2>Ember</h2>
        <p>
          Ember is the motorhome: house, studio, weather instrument, and occasional toaster. She is
          not glamorous. She is dependable in the way old boats are dependable, which is to say:
          mostly, and with character. This site is being written and built from inside her —
          between workdays, road days, cat negotiations, and whatever the weather allows.
        </p>

        <h2>The residents</h2>
        <p>
          The cats are the camp's permanent residents and its most honest critics. They review
          every parking spot within minutes of arrival and their standards are unreasonable. They
          appear in the notes from time to time, always without permission.
        </p>

        <ImagePlaceholder lang="en" note="A drawing of the camp — Ember, chairs, cats — will live here." />

        <h2>What gets collected here</h2>
        <p>
          Field notes from roadsides, rivers, cities, forests, and strange parking lots. Letters.
          Drawings. Bird sightings and other creature reports. Weather, both meteorological and
          emotional. Notes on making things, and on making a living without losing the plot. The
          slow record of a freer life being built in real time, mistakes included.
        </p>

        <h2>Why it exists</h2>
        <p>
          Because attention is a form of devotion, and wonder can be a practice. Because a small,
          strange, sincere life can become a body of work. Because the internet has enough
          platforms and not enough camps. And because — having gotten lost once inside a life that
          looked correct from the outside — the keeper of this camp does not intend to lose themself
          again, and writing it all down is part of how.
        </p>

        <p>
          If any of this sounds like your kind of place: stay a while. Read the
          <a href={routes.fieldNotes.en}>notes</a>, open a
          <a href={routes.softFootsteps.en}>letter</a>, or — if you are building something of your
          own and need a home for it — knock on the <a href={routes.studio.en}>studio</a> door.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTASection
    overline="Say hello"
    title="The camp receives visitors."
    text="Questions, letters, bird reports, website projects — the contact page is the camp's mailbox."
    cta={{ label: 'Go to contact', href: routes.contact.en }}
  />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-body {
    padding-block: var(--space-block) var(--space-section);
  }
</style>
